I tend to use the following code a lot, but jedi is unable to give completions on instance of cls:

```python
from PyQt5 import QtWidgets

class DlgPreferences(QtWidgets.QDialog):
    def __init__(self, parent):
        super().__init__()

    @classmethod
    def edit_preferences(cls, parent):
        dlg = cls(parent)
        dlg.  # no completion here
        cls.  # here I have some completions
```

This works fine in pycharm.

https://github.com/jonashaag/bjoern/blob/a090b0b5e01efa38bce9c0e33b92e5671ad7bc98/bjoern/server.c#L62
```
ev_signal_on_sigint(struct ev_loop* mainloop, ev_signal* watcher, const int events)
{
  /* Clean up and shut down this thread.
   * (Shuts down the Python interpreter if this is the main thread) */
  ev_unloop(mainloop, EVUNLOOP_ALL);
  PyErr_SetInterrupt();
}
```

This code bluntly interrupts request in processing. What is needed for graceful stop is ability to wait for current request to complete and only then raise exception or exit process.

